Observations based on the plots:

  • High female to male ratio in secondary education (Edu2.FM):
    • positively correlated with life expectancy (Life.Exp.) and expected years of education (Edu.Exp) (good things)
      • Edu.Exp and Edu2.FM are likely correlated as they are not really independent from each other
    • negatively correlated with maternal mortality (Mat.Mor) and adolecent births (Ado.Birth) (bad things)
    • it is maybe a bit surprisingly only very slightly or not correlated with parlamentary representation of women (Parli.F)
  • High female to male ratio (Labo.FM) is not correlated with Edu2.FM but seems to be positively correlated with Mat.Mort and Parl.F.

Explanation here

Principal component analysis without scaling the variables

Perform principal component analysis (PCA) on the raw (non-standardized) human data.

Show the variability captured by the principal components.

Draw a biplot displaying the observations by the first two principal components (PC1 coordinate in x-axis, PC2 coordinate in y-axis), along with arrows representing the original variables. (0-2 points)

# perform principal component analysis (with the SVD method) without scaling
not_scaled_human <- prcomp(human)

Principal component analysis for scaled variables

Scaling the variables:

# standardize the variables
human_std <- scale(human)

# print out summaries of the standardized variables
summary(human_std)

After scaling the variation seems to be more similar than before scaling.

Principal component analysis for scaled variables:

# perform principal component analysis (with the SVD method)
pca_human <- prcomp(human_std)

# draw a biplot of the principal component representation and the original variables
biplot(pca_human, choices = 1:2, cex = c(0.8, 1), col = c("grey40", "deeppink2"), main = "PCA with scaled 'human' data", xlab = "PC1 - female health and education", ylab = "PC2 - female labor force participation and parlamentary representation")

PCA reduces the variables into principle components represented by the axes

  • The variables in the plot are represented by the arrows.
  • If I understood this correctly, in this case PC2 is affected by Labo.FM and Parli.F, and the rest of the variables mainly affect PC1
    • If the variables are positively correlated, the angle between them is small
    • 90 degree angle - no correlation
    • 180 degree angle - negative correlation
  • The results here are similar as observed based on the ggpairs plot earlier:
    • Edu.Exp, Life.Exp, GNI and Edu2.FM are positively correlated with each other
    • Parli.F and Labo.FM are positively correlated with each other, but not really with other variables
    • Mat.Mort and Ado.Birth are positively with each other, and negatively correlated with Edu.Exp, Life.Exp, GNI and Edu2.FM
  • The observations that are more similar regarding these variables are clustered together
    • for example, Nordic countries appear very close to each other at the upper left corner
